00001 /* fflib/formation.h.  Generated by configure.  */
00002 /*
00003  * formation.h
00004  *
00005  * Programmer(s): Joe Mueller, David Wilson, Lavanya Swetharanyan, Stephanie Thomas
00006  *
00007  * Copyright 2005, Princeton Satellite Systems. All rights reserved.
00008  *
00009  *
00010  *
00011  *
00012  * NOTES
00013  * =====
00014  * 1.   I placed a "*sctlib" comment next to the functions that I think should go in sctlib. The group of 3-4
00015  *              functions at the bottom of this header should definitely go in sctlib.
00016  *
00017  * 2.   We should probably create a new structure "assignment_params" that includes {N, M, P, Pu, Q, phi, u, f}. 
00018  *              The first 7 params are returned from SetupAssignmentProblem, and the last one is the cost matrix that 
00019  *              gets filled during the distributed assignment process, created with InitializeCostMatrix.
00020  * 
00021  * 3.   The "NewtRaph" function is called by 3 other functions (FFEccXExt, ""YExt, ""ZExt). If its too hard to 
00022  *              implement as a seperate function, we can just perform the newton-raphson method seperately in each one.
00023  *
00024  * 4.   In the prototype, both julian date (JD) and seconds since 1970 (SS1970) units are used. In this library,
00025  *              we will use MET (a double in seconds) as the absolute time for referencing all time-tags. By using MET, 
00026  *              we can consistently use seconds to represent all times (orbit periods, timesteps, timetags, etc). 
00027  *              MET will be computed in the MANTA system by first creating a global ma_time_record called MST (mission
00028  *              start time), and then subtracting it from the current time.
00029  *
00030  *              side-note:  The ThrusterAlignment function requires the Julian Date because it needs to compute the
00031  *                                      location of the sun and moon with respect to the Earth. 
00032  *
00033  * 5.   There are many cases in which I've used "int", but we may want to use "unsigned short" to use less
00034  *              memory. For example, spacecraft ID numbers, which will always be postive and less than 10,000.
00035  *
00036  *
00037  *
00038  */
